main event: An unidentified object resembling a star with a circle around it was observed for 1.5 hours in the sky over Baltimore, Maryland on May 1, 1956.
interesting points: The object was the size of a grapefruit and descended below the horizon.
Winds were measured up to 65 knots from 270-290 degrees.
The object was initially observed at 65 degrees elevation in the ENE direction.
The object was observed through a small telescope, with its altitude changing but its azimuth remaining constant.
The report includes a description of the object's motion as 'jerky'.
sighted object: An unidentified object resembling a star with a circle around it
witnesses: 1 witness, Capt. John J. Miller, Operations Officer
